 code (uhv.http2.connection_header_rejected) when these headers are detected\n- Validates header names are lowercase (HTTP/2 requirement)\n- Rejects headers with uppercase letters (HTTP/2 compliance)\n- Rejects header names with underscores if configured (headers_with_underscores_action)\n- Validates empty header names are rejected\n\n### Path and Query Validation\n\n**Path Validation (source/extensions/http/header_validators/envoy_default/header_validator.cc)**\n- `validatePathHeaderCharacters()`: Validates path contains only RFC 3986 compliant characters\n- `sanitizeEncodedSlashes()`: Handles percent-encoded slashes (%2F, %5C) with configurable behavior\n- `sanitizePathWithFragment()`: Removes URL fragments from paths\n- `transformUrlPath()`: Normalizes paths and validates encoded sequences\n- Supports disabling path normalization while still validating character sets\n- Detects and prevents null byte injection (%00) in paths\n- Supports configurable character sets for path compliance modes\n\n### HTTP/3 (QUIC) Header Validation\n\n**QUIC Stream Validation (source/common/quic/envoy_quic_stream.h, source/common/quic/envoy_quic_server_stream.cc)**\n- `validateHeader()`: Per-header validation for QUIC streams using http2::adapter::HeaderValidator\n- Validates content-length headers for QUIC protocol requirements\n- Supports stream-specific error handling for invalid headers\n- Configuration option: override_stream_error_on_invalid_http_message\n- Validates header names and values against HTTP/2 semantics (QUIC uses HTTP/2 header encoding)\n\n**QUIC Utilities (source/common/quic/envoy_quic_utils.h)**\n- `quicHeadersToEnvoyHeaders()`: Converts QUIC headers to Envoy format with validation\n- Enforces max header count and size limits during conversion\n- Supports header validator interface for custom validation\n\n### Header Underscore Handling\n\n**Underscore Sanitization (source/extensions/http/header_validators/envoy_default/header_validator.cc)**\n- `sanitizeHeadersWithUnderscores()`: Drops or rejects headers containing underscores\n- Configurable via HeaderValidatorConfig.headers_with_underscores_action:\n  - ALLOW: Permits underscores\n  - DROP_HEADER: Silently removes headers with underscores\n  - REJECT_REQUEST: Returns validation error\n- Stats tracking for dropped headers\n\n### Runtime Configuration and Guards\n\nKey runtime guards controlling header validation behavior:\n- `envoy.reloadable_features.validate_upstream_headers`: Enables validation of upstream request headers\n- `envoy.reloadable_features.sanitize_te`: Enables TE header sanitization\n- `envoy.reloadable_features.consistent_header_validation`: RFC-compliant header validation\n- `envoy.reloadable_features.sanitize_http2_headers_without_nghttp2`: Header validation without nghttp2\n- `envoy.uhv.allow_non_compliant_characters_in_path`: Compatibility mode for path characters\n\n### Architecture Summary\n\nThe header injection prevention is enforced at multiple levels:\n\n1. **Codec Level**: HTTP/1, HTTP/2, and HTTP/3 codecs validate headers during parsing\n2. **Connection Manager Level**: The connection manager sanitizes internal headers and applies transformations\n3. **Header Validator Extensions**: Pluggable header validators provide protocol-specific validation\n4. **Utility Functions**: Shared utility functions handle common validation patterns (hostname, method, scheme)\n5. **Header Map Level**: The base HeaderMap class validates header strings cannot contain control characters\n\nThis multi-layered approach ensures comprehensive protection against HTTP request header injection attacks across all supported HTTP protocols, with configurable behavior for different security and compatibility requirements."
